<br>
I'll throw two examples onto the table here.<br>
<br>
First one.  Xotal.  My character has a talking sword.  It sounds utterly ridiculous, and it is.  I can make him talk (I don't do it very often, but hell, I manage it), but for everything I try, I have to do it in ways that don't actually fit into the world.  Xotal is rarely mentioned by name, he's just known as /em 's sword.  It can make it ridiculously difficult to actually emote his more complex situations, because I like complex characters with a full range of emotions (that said, /em smiles and /em grins comes up a lot, mainly because I play my character as a nice sorta guy who does a lot of grinning and smiling, but that's aside the point).  The thing is, I'd love to actually be able to give the sword more life, but I can only do it in out of game story.  It's the only place where I honestly have enough control over the environment he's in.<br>
<br>
Secondly, emotions.  Very, very, very difficult to do without making it read like a script IMO.  Coupled with the image of two static models sat 35 feet away from each other, they tend to...  taper off somewhat.  *shrugs*  Maybe I'm just a crap roleplayer, I dunno *grins* <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ujelineth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jelineth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/24/02 9:59:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1272.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Not a flame/complaint/anything else</span><hr size=1> Try playing a blind druid. Ever have to explain why you can move around as well as a sighted person? Tell them the trees are talking to you. You talk about getting more mentions of crazy. But you know what. it is something that is fun to me.<br>
